<HL> Now, After 91 Years, Dow Chemical Co. May Change Name --- Problem Word Is 'Chemical': The Public Distrusts It, So Most Firms Drop It </HL>
<AUTHOR> Bradley A. Stertz (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> DOW </CO>
<IN> CHM </IN>
<TEXT>
   Dow Chemical Co. is thinking about changing its name after 91 years and numerous image-wrenching controversies. 

   Dow officials confirmed they have hired a corporate image consultant and organized a team internally to consider whether a new name would help the company's image. 
At issue is whether Dow should keep the word 'chemical' in its name. 
The Midland, Mich., company is one of the last major chemical corporations to do so. 

   "Let's face it," says Richard K. Long, Dow Chemical's corporate communications director, who is heading the name-change study: "That word does nobody much good these days. 
Chemical has a less than desirable public connotation." 

   The public has tended to associate 'chemical' companies with pollution and other health hazards. 

   Dow officials also dislike the word chemical because it fails to identify Dow's involvement in other businesses such as consumer products and pharmaceuticals. 
"It's a question of whether we're a chemical company or a company that happens to practice chemistry," Mr. Long said. 

   Disdain for the C-word is nothing new in the chemical industry. 
St. Louis-based Monsanto Co. dropped 'chemical' from its name in 1964 when the company diversified into other businesses. 
But Monsanto also wanted to distance itself from public outcry against chemical companies in general. 
"There's a school of thought that if you've got that word in your name, you're a target for trouble," a Monsanto official says. 

   DuPont Co., the nation's largest chemical concern, even went so far as to drop the end of its corporate slogan, which once read: "Better things for better living through chemistry." 

   Still, Dow stubbornly clung to its name. 
The company stayed with it in the 1960s when Vietnam War protestors criticized Dow for its napalm production. 
Uproars over dioxin, Agent Orange and other environmental contaminations traced to Dow also failed to convince company executives to make a switch. 

   "Basically, the thinking was our customers knew who we were with our old name and they weren't reacting negatively to the controversies," says Mr. Long. 

   There is also a lot of tradition working against changing the name, which the company has had since Herbert H. Dow founded it in 1897. 
Many executives see the continuity as a source of corporate pride. 

   But the negative associations with the word chemical may win the day. 
The name-change study is a continuation of the company's recent efforts to project a friendlier public image, sparked by former chief executive officer Paul F. Oreffice, who said a name change might do the company some good. 

   In January, Dow hired the New York image firm Anspach Grossman Portugal Inc. for help with the idea and has since assigned 14 of its own people to work with the project. 

   Not that Dow will stray far from its current name. 
Mr. Long insists that the Dow part will stay, although no final recommendations have been given to top management. 
"Maybe it will be Dow Industries," he says. 
"We want something that won't make us look like we're running away to hide from anything." 

</TEXT>
</DOC>

