<TEXT>     And in Tehran, the Iranian government accused Baghdad of kidnapping the
world's highest-ranking Shiite scholar and forcing him to show support for
Saddam.;    Those accusations reflected the mounting tensions between Saddam
and his internal and external enemies over the methods used by Iraq to put
down its bloody civil war.;    Bayan Jabr, a spokesman for the Supreme Council
of the Islamic Revolution in Iraq, said 15,000 civilians had been killed in
the past four days in the holy Shiite city of Najaf, south of Baghdad.;   
Jabr, speaking from Nicosia, Cyprus, said the Iraqi government has been
attacking Shiites with napalm and white phosphorous bombs and that "many
civilians were martyred.";    In addition, Syrian radio quoted Jabr's
organization as saying "many civilians were martyred when sulfuric acid was
dropped on Kirkuk, which is controlled by the popular forces.";    U.S.
military officials in Saudi Arabia said they had no knowledge of acid being
dropped on Kirkuk.;    Iran's official news agency said the Tehran government
had strongly protested Iraq's reported abduction of Grand Ayatollah Abolqassen
Al-Khoei, the foremost Shiite authority. He is more than 90 years old. He was
shown on Iraqi television Wednesday congratulating Saddam for stomping out
sedition by the Shiites.;    State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
rebels remained in control Thursday of large portions of the predominantly
Kurdish areas of northern Iraq, including areas close to the cities of Kirkuk
and Mosul.;    Boucher reported "heavy fighting . . . in the immediate
vicinity of the city of Kirkuk and probably inside the city itself.";    He
said fighting also was continuing in southern Iraq with "some particularly
heavy fighting taking place" in the vicinity of the holy city of Karbala.;   
However, reports of the fighting in Iraq could not be confirmed independently
because Iraq has banned all foreign reporters from the country.;    Kurdish
guerrilla leader Jalal Talabani said he would return to Iraq this weekend to
join forces with other opposition leaders.;    "This is the spring of freedom
for Kurdistan," he said.;    Also Thursday, an Iraqi delegation in the Saudi
capital of Riyadh began talks with allied officials on speeding up the
repatriation of Iraqi prisoners of war. Iraq freed 1,150 Kuwaitis on Thursday
in compliance with cease-fire terms, but thousands more are believed to have
been taken captive by Iraq during its seven-month occupation of Kuwait.;    At
the United Nations, the United States circulated a proposal requiring Iraq to
accept the destruction of its nuclear weapons-grade materials, ballistic
missiles and chemical and biological weapons before the overall embargo is
lifted and the allied cease-fire made permanent.  </TEXT>
