held by a Saudi soldier at a distribution center near Safwan, Iraq.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  IRAQ; MIDEAST; WAR; CIVIL; VIOLENCE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  It's as if a piece of hell has appeared on earth, here on the eastern fringe
of the Shamiya Desert. Oil wells burn. Iraqi mines and cluster bombs blow up
children at play. Hundreds of refugees wander about, lost in the sands of a
soulless land.;    It's sundown on Saturday. But not even the sun can pierce
the folds of the oily veil of sky and shine clearly through. The air in
U.S.-occupied Iraq smells sweet and warm by day, like a very busy gas station
on a Saturday afternoon in any American town.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  INNOCENTS TRAPPED IN BORDER HELL  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  TURMOIL IN THE MIDEAST
See also related stories on pages 1A and 18A, 19A and 21A of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     But with night's advance, an icy rain turns the desert into an oozing stew.
Lightning comes in great broad strokes against the smoke screen that passes
here for sky. Later, there will be Iraqi artillery fire in the distance,
bright orange tracer bullets and flares slitting the damp darkness.;    Here
between Kuwait and Iraq, there is neither war nor peace -- only varying
degrees of dying. In the long food and medical lines in what is left of the
village of Safwan, 5,000 Iraqi citizens and refugees depend now on the mercy
of American GIs for survival.;    "Last month we were killing them," said Army
Lt. Col John Kalb. "This month we're fixing them.";    Kalb is not as flippant
as he may sound. Without him and his soldiers, the people here would very soon
start to die. Kuwait considers them enemies; Iraq considers them traitors. In
this vise grip of international politics, the children are filthy and
fatherless and resorting to roadside pantomime to cop candy from passing Land
Cruisers full of reporters.;    "Someone from the State Department came
through here yesterday," Kalb said. "They must have noticed these people need
help, because, before we knew it, we were out here passing out food rations
and bottled water. There wasn't anyone helping them, and that's the trick bag
they're in now.";    As captured Iraqi ammunition dumps are blown up by
Americans off in the desert distance, babies are brought to medics at Army
checkpoints, dehydrated and cradled by mothers fleeing the terror of civil war
in Basra and Nassariyah. But with the rebellion now apparently faltering in
these cities, the children's wounds seen by Army doctor Carolyn Sullivan are
no longer the wounds of war, but rather the wounds of its terrible legacy.;   
"We're seeing some children burned by old ordnance that exploded when they
picked it up or walked on it," said Sullivan. "I'm seeing kids with parts of
limbs blown off, kids burned from picking up things that blow up in their
hands." Friday, her unit treated 191 people in a tent beside the road to
Nassariyah.;    Every soldier here has a horror story.;    Jeff Robinson, an
Arabic interpreter from the Utah National Guard, has seen a 2-year-old with
shrapnel wounds in her shoulder.;    At another checkpoint farther up the
road, Army Sgt. Zachary Madsen said he had a father and son walk up to him
recently. The son's entire left leg was burned -- by Iraqi army napalm, the
father said. "It was a real deep burn, blistered and black," Madsen said. "The
man said four of his children died in their home from the bomb and the
napalm.";    These checkpoints are little desert isles of homesick soldiers
dug in at abandoned overpasses, suspended somewhere between bored and bonkers.
Around them lies a lonesome junkyard of burned-out tanks and armored personnel
carriers, the legacy of Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's mistake of a battle.;
   Nothing seems quite right out here: You see the burned-out husks of cars in
the middle lane. You see trucks driving backward down exits. You see buses
blown to smithereens. And you see Iraqi refugees wandering off into the sands,
or Iraqi soldiers scurrying along the highway in the rain, trying desperately
to turn themselves in to the Americans.;    Two young Iraqi men -- one
claiming to be a teacher of Arabic, the other a student at the college in
Basra -- flag down a car, the only one to come along in a half-hour.;    They
had just tried to cross a checkpoint, but "the American soldiers sent us
back," says the student, who is afraid to have his name appear in print.
"Saddam Hussein has killed all the people. We all hate Saddam Hussein, but we
are not strong enough to fight him. He hit Karpala with napalm and chemicals.
He killed us in the streets like dogs.";    Asked if he knew anyone personally
who had been killed, the man grows agitated. "Yes!" he shouts. "They killed my
mother. And they killed some of my neighbors.;    "But now we put our fate in
America's hands. If we go back, Saddam will kill us. What can we do? All the
doors have been closed to us now.";    Even farther up the road, at the last
and deepest American checkpoint inside Iraq, four soldiers huddle inside a
tent beside the highway. This is the end of the American road, the official
line of demarcation etched out on military maps at meetings between the Iraqis
and the allies. Beyond it about 500 yards, Iraqi soldiers operate their own
last checkpoint before the enemy area begins.;    "We're picking up quite a
few Iraqi soldiers," said Staff Sgt. Joe Stewart, 34, of Alexandria, Ky. "We
search them for weapons, then send them south to the next checkpoint, where
they're processed as enemy prisoners of war."  </TEXT>
