<DESCRIPT>  RELIGION; ETHICS; LETTER  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  JOAN Connell usually writes creditable stuff, but "Rules of Engagement," her
Jan. 23 article on military ethics, is indefensible.;    Napalm and white
phosphorous are being used against Iraqi soldiers. Those are among the most
fiendish of chemical weapons, intended to torture and disfigure before
killing. The new "daisy cutter" bomb is so big that it cannot be carried by
bombers and must be pushed out of transport planes -- hardly a precision
delivery plan.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Religion &amp; Ethics  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'INDEFENSIBLE' STANCE ON MILITARY ETHICS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Letters  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The "daisy cutter" wreaks death and destruction on an area the equivalent
of 50 football fields, sucking oxygen and blood from those beneath it as it
explodes just above ground level. According to British defense consultants,
the tonnage of high explosives released in the gulf war has exceeded the
combined air offensive of World War II.;    Connell reports that "lawyers from
all branches of the service are on the battlefield." What a cruel,
unbelievable and impossible hoax! Ask any infantryman, any Marine when was the
last time he saw a lawyer nearby on the front lines.;    Where were the
lawyers when the United States bombed civilians in Panama or when bombing
victims were hurriedly buried in mass graves? Where were the ethicists when
the Contras were being provided with manuals advising how to administer
psychological and physical torture?;    Connell further misleads her readers
by stating that decisions about the use of napalm, white phosphorous and other
unthinkable weapons pose a moral dilemma for field commanders. Such decisions
are made at the highest level, which presumably includes the commander in
chief.;    The B-52 carpet bombing is a terror decision made by Secretary of
Defense Dick Cheney, Joint Chiefs of Staff chairman Colin Powell and President
Bush. By dropping more bombs than in all of World War II, the United States
has made a decision to use terror against the citizens and soldiers of Iraq.; 
  Those who advocate the use of those terror weapons take a higher moral
ground than those who try to clothe the use in some ethical and moral
camouflage. The former at least take responsibility for their statements.;   
Connell has inadvertently played the role of apologist for our government's
use of terror. I suggest that if she really wants to test the legal and
ethical standards of our government when it comes to warfare, she should find
out when the United States intends to pay the $16 billion in reparations to
Nicaragua as ordered by the World Court.;    Al Traugott; San Jose  </TEXT>
