<LEADPARA>  With Wall Street cautious on the eve of a crucial weekend in the Persian Gulf
war, investors pulled back Friday in heavy trading after a strong rally.;   
In a steep one-hour selling wave starting at 2:11 p.m., the Dow Jones
industrial average plunged nearly 60 points, or 2 percent, from its high for
the day.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  STOCKS RALLY, THEN RETREAT; DOW FALLS 2  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Chart attached at end of article
The Associated Press contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     After being ahead 44, the Dow ended the day off 2.47 at 2,889.36, putting
the loss for the week at 45.29, or 1.5 percent.;    What touched off the
flurry was a report that U.S. warplanes had dropped napalm on Iraqi front
lines.;    It was later confirmed that napalm had been dumped into oil-filled
trenches in front of enemy lines to try to burn off the oil.;    "The market's
falling out of bed," one Wall Street analyst remarked. "People want out over
the weekend as a protective measure.";    Other stock averages showed little
change, suggesting the weakness was largely in blue chips.;    The broader
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index ended at 365.65, up less than a point for the day.
The NASDAQ and Amex composites both gained slightly.;    New York Stock
Exchange volume rose to 218.8 million shares from 180.8 million Thursday.;   
Showing that traders were indecisive, 820 Big Board stocks advanced, while 715
declined.;    Even so, no stock dropped to a new low -- the first time that
has happened in several years -- while 104 rose to new highs.;    One of the
new highs was General Mills, which reached 54 3/4 before falling to 53 1/4, up
1 1/4.;    The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond closed unchanged from
Thursday, with its yield remaining at 8.06 percent.;    Among the 30 Dow
industrials, IBM slid 2 1/4 to 133 1/4, in heavy trading. International Paper,
one of several paper companies downgraded by Richard Schneider of Kidder,
Peabody, fell 1 3/8 to 62 3/8.;    Despite the drop in IBM, other
high-technology stocks fared well.;    Microsoft rose 2 1/4 to 102 1/4; Adobe
Systems, 2 to 47 1/2; and Shared Medical Systems, 1 to 18 1/8.;    Applied
Materials, which will triple the size of its Japanese semiconductor factory,
rose 1 5/8 to 31 1/4, and Motorola rose 1 7/8 to 63 1/8.;    AST Research rose
6 5/8 to 52 1/2 for a new NASDAQ high of 52 3/4, and Compaq rose 1 1/8 to 72
3/4.;    Sun Microsystems rose 1 5/8 to 32 1/4 as the most active NASDAQ stock
after it and Hewlett-Packard said they would announce a joint development deal
Monday.;    H-P rose 1/8 to 47 3/8.;    Amgen rose 6 1/4 to 101 3/4, after
setting higher-than-expected prices on a chemotherapy drug, prompting analysts
to raise their earnings estimates.;    Immunex, which said it expected
