<DESCRIPT>  IRAQ; CIVIL; VIOLENCE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Iraq's civil war has become a bloodbath, with loyalist Republican Guard forces
reportedly using artillery, helicopter gunships and napalm to put down Iraqi
rebels.;    Members of the 82nd Airborne Division based near the Iraqi city of
Nassariyah said more than 600 civilians injured in the fighting had sought
assistance from U.S. Army doctors in the last two weeks. Women and children,
their faces shattered by gunshots or their bodies torn by bombs, have been
among the injured, they said.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GROWING IRAQI CIVIL WAR BECOMES A BLOODBATH
IRAQI TROOPS 'BUTCHERING' EVEN CHILDREN  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  TURMOIL IN THE MIDEAST
See also related stories on pages 1A and 8A of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "They are butchering people by the hundreds -- using artillery, helicopter
gunships," said Sgt. Jim Parker of the 82nd Airborne, referring to Republican
Guard troops who remain loyal to Iraqi President Saddam Hussein. "This is as
close to hell as you can get.";    Refugees estimated that about 5,000 bodies
were on the streets of the southern city of Basra, and Iran's official
government radio reported that thousands of civilians had been killed along
the road between Karbala and Najaf.;    After a two-week media blackout on the
rebellion, Saddam's embattled government has launched a campaign to turn
public opinion against the insurgents.;    "It was all blood, blood, blood,"
said a story Monday in Iraq's government newspaper. Baghdad dailies splashed
photos and stories of the burgeoning civil war across their front pages.;   
"The barbarism and brutality of the U.S. aggression against Iraq was not
isolated from all the crimes that took place after the cease-fire at the hands
of mobs, agents and outlaws," declared the military newspaper Al Qadissiya,
blaming the allied victors in the Persian Gulf war for inciting insurrection.;
   Saturday, Saddam himself, speaking publicly for the first time since the
100-hour ground war, put the blame on Iran, which he accused of stirring
Shiite Muslims in southern Iraq to rise against the Baghdad government.;   
Iraq's apparent inability to quickly crush the revolt emboldened some of
Saddam's opponents to predict Monday that his downfall was all but assured.;  
 "Saddam's days in power are numbered. He will be removed very shortly,"
Hassan Nakib, a former Iraqi Army general and leader of one of the exiled
opposition groups, said in Damascus, Syria.;    Nakib said tens of thousands
of Iraqi soldiers had switched sides in the battle. The rebels, he maintained,
now control most Iraqi cities and towns.;    Iran's ranking cleric also
declared that Saddam would soon fall.;    The Iranian radio said Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei, Iran's religious leader, told a group of visiting Palestinian and
Lebanese leaders in Tehran on Monday that the Saddam government could not
endure for long "because of the arms that have fallen into the hands of the
people.";    What Saddam's regime has not yet been able to put down by force,
the Iraqi president apparently has decided, will be attacked with a propaganda
barrage as well.;    A reporter for the government daily Al Jumhuriyah was
dispatched to the key southern city of Karbala, revered by the Shiite sect as
the burial place of its earliest imams, or religious leaders.;    Like other
correspondents for the government press, Jumhuriyah's man said rebels had
rampaged through the city, killing innocents and destroying property. Bodies
were stacked in Karbala's hospitals, he wrote. "Blood was painted on the
streets and the walls of the city. It was all blood, blood, blood.";    Al
Thawra, the newspaper of Hussein's ruling Arab Baath Socialist Party, said the
insurgency in the south was meant to destroy Iraq and "turn it into another
Lebanon.";    Saddam's government insisted that the rebellion in the south was
ethnically based on the Shiite majority there and was being stirred up and
agitated by the Shiite regime in neighboring Iran. Ayatollah Khamenei
reinforced the relationship when he declared a day of mourning in Iran for
"the massacre of Iraq's defenseless people by the Baathist criminals.";    In
Safwan, near the Kuwait border, refugees described increasingly violent
fighting.;    "We saw children with burns like holes in their feet, and we
were told it was napalm," said Jamal Rifai, 45, a Kuwaiti citizen recently
released by rebels from a prison in Kerbala. "It had burned through the skin.
We had heard it had been used in Basra and Najaf.";    Saddam "is burning the
bodies," said Raad Hasem, a 38-year-old farmer, en route from Safwan to Basra
to sell his tomatoes. "The bombs dropped from the helicopters, and the bodies
burned quickly.";    "We were eating animal feed before we left," said Sahid
Shaban, an Egyptian mechanic who fled Basra on Monday and arrived in
allied-controlled territory near Kuwait. "We would grind it up and eat it with
sea water.";    Shaban, who had lived in Basra for nine years, said the city
was "full of bodies. Dogs are eating them everywhere. There is no food, no
water.";    In addition to the Shiite rebellion in the south, Kurdish
guerrillas are waging their own battle with the Baghdad government in the
north.  </TEXT>
