<HEAD>Government Bombs Strategic Fort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air force planes and helicopters
firebombed and strafed residential areas near Jaffna Fort, a
strategic military garrison, and hundreds of buildings were ablaze,
Tamil rebels said Tuesday.
   Authorities and witnesses reported the deaths of 196 people
nationwide, bringing the death toll in two weeks of fighting to
1,626 combatants. Many civilians have also been killed.
   In the northern city of Jaffna, the rebel stronghold, the
government used bombers and a helicopter gunship to pound
residential areas around Jaffna Fort, in which 270 soldiers and
policemen have been besieged since the fighting began.
   Five air force bombers and a helicopter gunship used 120-pound
bombs and 66-pound incendiary devices in the attack, said a rebel
statement telexed to newspaper and news agency offices in Colombo.
   It described attacks on Monday and said hundreds of buildings
near Jaffna Fort were set on fire. ``The whole area is ablaze,'' it
said.
   Military officials said Tuesday that air force planes continued
to bomb and strafe rebel positions and were trying to avoid
civilian targets in the city, 186 miles north of Colombo.
   ``We are not hellbent on bombing and killing people,'' Defense
Secretary Gen. Cyril Ranatunge said.
   There was no way to independently verify rebel or government
claims because transportation and telephone services to the region
were cut off.
   But travelers reaching Vavuniya, just south of Jaffna, confirmed
that the Jaffna was being heavily bombed.
   Over the weekend, air force planes dropped leaflets warning the
city's 120,000 residents to evacuate.
   The rebel statement claimed the military was using ``napalm''
bombs but then said the bombs were made of coal tar, rubber
shavings and explosives. There was no indication that napalm, a
powerful defoliant, was used by the military.
   The government considers Jaffna Fort one of its main bases in
the area and it would be a serious military blow if it lost the
area to the rebels.
   The Tamils started a war for separatism in 1983 but there had
been a 13-month halt to hostilities during a cease-fire between the
rebels and the Sinhalese-dominated government.
   The latest fighting broke out on June 11, after a Tamil man
claimed he was manhandled by Sinhalese police. Tamil Tigers then
overran a series of police stations.
   Tamils form 18 percent of the island's 16 million people. They
have long accused the Sinhalese majority of discrimination.
</TEXT>
