<LEADPARA>  AS many as 2 million Kurds are fleeing toward or into Iran and Turkey, as
Saddam Hussein crushes the remnants of the uprising against him. The world
must at least keep these refugees fed, clothed, sheltered and safe.;    The
nations of the European Community have proposed to establish havens for the
Kurds inside Iraq, near the border with Turkey. Already the United States has
begun flying in supplies.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  REFUGE FOR KURDS
AIDING WOUNDED, STARVING REFUGEES IS THE
LEAST THAT THE UNITED STATES CAN DO  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Editorials  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Although help is on the way, the Kurds understandably feel betrayed. The
United States and the European Community were there before the rebellion,
pummeling Saddam and encouraging revolt.;    Now that Saddam has again
massacred Kurds, the Western powers are there with aid. But where were they
when the bullets, the bombs and the napalm were raining down?;    If only it
were that simple.;    The United Nations resolutions against Iraq authorized
force to liberate Kuwait. That was done, with gusto. The allies used more
force than necessary to accomplish the narrow goal. Iraq's -- meaning Saddam's
-- military was crushed for any international purpose.;    In Saddam's defeat,
Kurds in the north and Shiites in the south thought they saw their chance to
remove a brutal dictator.;    They misjudged. Saddam's remaining forces were
plenty to crush the rebellion. Lacking a U.N. mandate and torn between the two
principles of national sovereignty and human rights, the United States and the
Europeans stood by.;    We thought President Bush was right to resist
intervening militarily to support the Kurds, even though he had been careless
in inciting them to revolt.;    Now, with the Kurds staggering, the principle
is simpler. Aid to refugees is less problematic than aid to armed rebels. This
may be the most we should do, but it is also the least we can do.;    Any
assertion from Saddam that the camps violate Iraq's sovereignty should be
rejected. Saddam's massacre of Kurds has gone far beyond suppressing an armed
rebellion; it approaches genocide. International law permits intervention to
stop it.;    The latest horrors -- napalm and machine-gunning refugees from
helicopters -- are terrible reminders of the poison-gas massacre of 5,000
Kurds in 1988. Kurds cannot be expected to believe promises of amnesty from
Saddam.;    As solutions born of desperation usually do, the havens will
create difficulties. Will they become crowded refugee camps that seem to exist
indefinitely and condemn their inhabitants to years of limbo, like Gaza or
camps in Thailand? What if Iraq attacks them as sources of insurrection with
the country?;    Hundreds of thousands of men, women and children, who may die
from the elements or by Saddam's hand, can't wait for answers. Help now;
figure it out later.  </TEXT>
