<DESCRIPT>  US; MILITARY; ASSAULT; MIDEAST; WAR; IRAQ  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The U.S.-led ground campaign opened across multiple fronts Saturday, closely
tracking the Pentagon's battle plan calling for a stunning mix of speed and
firepower from several directions to isolate and, if necessary, destroy the
Iraqi forces.;    If all goes according to plan, the campaign will be wrapped
up in days or weeks, with U.S. deaths in the hundreds, one defense official
said. But experienced military analysts outside the Pentagon have said the war
could drag on for more than a month and kill thousands of Americans.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ALLIED STRATEGY: HIT IRAQIS FAST, HARD
PLAN IS TO ISOLATE TROOPS FROM BAGHDAD COMMAND  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  WAR IN THE GULF
See also related stories on pages 1A and 16-24A of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Because the Iraqi military has long relied on orders issued from
headquarters, Pentagon officials believe that the allies' shredding of Iraq's
command and control network during 38 days of bombing will dramatically
shorten the war: "If they can't communicate, they can't coordinate," one Army
officer said. "That means there won't be one big war but a lot of little
ones.";    U.S. war planners have spent the past seven months retooling their
war plan, which was originally designed for the defense of Europe, for
retaking Kuwait.;    "A considerable additional amount of violence is
available to the commander should it be decided to use that violence," Army
Lt. Gen. Thomas W. Kelly, director of operations for the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, said Saturday before the ground war began. "If the ground attack
occurs, there will be no doubt in anybody's mind -- especially in the minds of
the Iraqi soldiers -- that it has occurred.";    Details kept secret;  Even
after the ground war got under way, details remained a closely held secret.
But the broad outlines have become increasingly clear as 735,000 troops from
28 nations moved into position to battle the approximately 500,000 Iraqi
troops dug into Kuwait and southern Iraq.;    At the western edge of the
battle zone, allied forces have probably lunged directly into Iraq from Saudi
Arabia to seal off Iraqi troops in Kuwait and southern Iraq, including the
vaunted Republican Guard. Once the allied forces sever the Iraqis'
communications and supply lines, they will move south and attack the trapped
Iraqi troops from the rear, where the Iraqis' extensive earthwork
fortifications would be worthless.;    On the eastern side of the war zone, in
the northern Persian Gulf, about 18,000 Marines aboard 31 vessels are expected
to hit Kuwaiti beaches and quickly seek to liberate Kuwait City, the capital
of the occupied country. The leathernecks will come ashore aboard landing
ships, land-sea vehicles that hover on a layer of air, and helicopters.;   
Between those two potential fronts, on either side of where the borders of
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and Iraq meet, U.S. armored units have breached the broad
mine fields, oil-filled moats, razor wire and sand berms at at least two
points, defense officials said.;    U.S. Army M-1 tanks began slashing through
the berms early Saturday, preparing paths for thousands of allied troops to
pour through in additional tanks and Bradley Fighting Vehicles. Above, Marine
AV-8 Harrier jets dropped 500-pound napalm bombs into the oil-filled moats
along the Saudi-Kuwaiti border, seeking to drain or exhaust the moats' fuel
before an allied attack.;    Engineers in lead;  At the tip of the allied
spear Saturday were Army combat engineers, clad in bulky chemical protective
suits, stretching portable bridges across moats and trenches. Explosive
charges and rakes and rollers pushed by tanks were used to detonate mines that
survived allied bombing meant to destroy them.;    U.S. officials have played
down the significance of Iraq's chemical weapons capability, except to hint
that the United States would respond furiously to its use, both on the
battlefield and in war crimes trials later.;    Tanks and fighting vehicles
followed the engineers into Kuwait, seeking to flush the Iraqi tanks from
their holes. Air Force A-10s and Army Apache and Cobra gunships fired Hellfire
missiles and 30mm cannon at Iraqi tanks that moved.;    To attack tanks that
remain dug in, allied infantry members will most likely jump from the Bradleys
and engage surviving Iraqis in what Pentagon officials believe will be the
conflict's bloodiest phase: "They'll have machine guns instead of bayonets,"
one Army officer said.;    With the traditional "fog of war" thickened by a
black pall of smoke from nearly 200 oil fires inside Kuwait, additional
"friendly fire" deaths among allied forces are virtually certain, U.S.
officials admit.;    Meanwhile, Army helicopters are unloading hundreds of
soldiers to capture or hastily build air strips inside Kuwait and Iraq. Within
hours, C-130 cargo planes will begin ferrying fresh U.S. troops into Kuwait
and Iraq and flying allied casualties from the battle zone.  </TEXT>
