<DESCRIPT>  IRAQ; KUWAIT; US; MIDEAST; WAR; MILITARY; ETHICS; REGULATION; LIST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  TO THOSE who are opposed to killing of any kind, military ethics is a
contradiction in terms, a sick joke, a convenient rationalization that places
the carnage of battle on a pedestal of moral respectability.;    But
professional soldiers have long considered this unavoidably bloody business to
be an art as well as a science. And though human history is littered with grim
examples of the breakdown of moral order on the battlefield, rules of
engagement have always governed the game.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Religion &amp; Ethics  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE RULES OF ENGAGEMENT
ETHICISTS AND MILITARY EXPERTS TRY TO MAP
OUT A MORAL CODE OF WAR  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story
War in the Gulf
Additional information attached to the end of this article.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     In Biblical times, it was forbidden to destroy orchards of the enemy.
Medieval warriors were enjoined from poisoning village wells. In the American
Civil War, a confederate officer was convicted of murder for the mistreatment
of Union soldiers at Andersonville Prison. In the Vietnam War, Lt. William
Calley was found guilty of murder for his role in the My Lai massacre.;   
Today, as the diplomatic deadline looms for Saddam Hussein to leave Kuwait,
allied artillery continues to batter Iraqi positions. And two massive armies
are still poised to engage in a land battle.;    Whether the dreaded ground
war will occur is at this point unknown. What is known, however is that in the
gulf war, as perhaps never before in U.S. military history, the rules of
engagement are playing an important symbolic and practical role:;    (box)
Lawyers from all branches of the service are on the battlefront, advising
military strategists on how to tailor battle plans to minimize civilian
casualties and manage enemy prisoners.;    (box) Legal experts confer almost
daily with Pentagon officials about target lists to guide the thousands of
bombing missions over Iraq away from civilian areas and religious sites.;   
(box) Every soldier receives some training in the legal aspects of war. Combat
troops carry cards on how to treat prisoners.;    "Marines do not harm enemies
who surrender," reads one such battlefield ethical guide. "They must disarm
them and turn them over to their superiors. Marines do not kill or torture
prisoners. Marines collect and care for the wounded, whether friend or foe."; 
  To Nicholas Fotion, who teaches military ethics at Emory University in
Atlanta, the heightened ethical awareness in the gulf war has both tactical
and moral value.;    "In some strange sense, it's probably profitable to be
ethical," says Fotion, a professor of philosophy and author of "Military
Ethics: Looking Toward the Future," newly published by the Hoover Institution
at Stanford University. "Insofar as we fight an ethical war, the military
retains support in the United States and it maintains the support among our
allies.";    Saddam's decision to take the ethical low road in this war --
displaying downed, possibly tortured American pilots on Iraqi television;
fouling Persian Gulf waters with a massive oil slick (to which Allied bombing
may, however, have contributed); and Friday, in possible retreat, setting
hundreds of Kuwaiti oil wells afire -- may only enhance the allied forces'
position, in Fotion's view.;    "Being good, tactically speaking, pays off,"
Fotion says. "Our military realizes that in this war, because we have such a
great military advantage, we should not respond in kind. If they use poison
gas, or start shooting prisoners, we should not retaliate. If we did, the
delicate alliance we have fashioned with the Arab nations would quickly fall
apart.";    High-tech terror;  Fotion is confident that through diplomacy and
the high-tech weaponry that gave allied forces the military edge, this war
will end soon. But he is less confident about the conduct of future wars, in
which smart bombs and laser-guided weapons systems will become increasingly
available.;    "In the hands of ruthless commanders, the weapons created by
technology seem irresistibly to allow them to commit atrocities much more
swiftly than before," he says.;    "In the gulf war, technology is obviously
not all bad. In fact, where one side has significant technological advantage
over another, technology seems to make fighting an ethically clean war far
more possible. But what would happen if two high-technology powers of roughly
equal strength got into a fight? An all-out high-tech war would be dirty by
its very nature.";    But as tensions mount in the hours before the diplomatic
deadline, so do ethical dilemmas to commanders in the field. Reports surfaced
from Saudi Arabia on Friday that waves of U.S. airplanes rained napalm and
deadly fuel-air bombs onto Iraqi defenses.;    Vietnam's lessons;  Fotion says
the enhanced ethical awareness of the military in the gulf war is a legacy of
the Vietnam War, a military encounter rife with moral ambiguities for the
nation and for the soldiers in the field.;    The guerrilla nature of the
conflict made it hard for soldiers to distinguish friend from foe. And the My
Lai massacre, in which American soldiers raped and murdered Vietnamese
villagers, became an emblem of the war's skewed moral compass.;    Trying to
teach morality;  "The military has learned its lessons from Vietnam," Fotion
says. "In the past, the military academies taught military strategy and how to
kill people. Now, courses in ethics are required of all cadets. Those courses
were not in place 20 years ago.";    Col. Kenneth Wenker, professor of
philosophy at the Air Force Academy in Colorado Springs, says there has been a
subtle shift of emphasis across the curriculum to emphasize ethics.;    "When
presented with an ethical or moral dilemma, there's a tendency to have a
knee-jerk reaction and declare a situation all black or all white," Wenker
says. "But with some training, people learn to deal with ambiguity.;    "We
simply have to insist on the integrity of individuals," he adds. "We have to
insist that our people understand the moral reasons of why we go to war. What
we're doing has a moral dimension.";    Fotion just received first-hand
evidence from a former student, now serving as a Marine, addressing the moral
dimensions of what is going on in this war.;    "I got a letter from him the
other day in which he talked about the dirty tricks the Iraqi soldiers played
in the battle at Khafji," Fotion says, referring to an episode in which Iraqis
drove tanks toward allied forces with their guns facing backward. Perceiving
it as a traditional sign of surrender, the allied forces held their fire. When
the Iraqi tanks got closer, they turned the guns around and began firing.;   
"This student was so angry about this kind of tactic, he wrote he'd take
scalps from dead Iraqis soldiers and bring them home as trophies in
retaliation," Fotion says. "I fired off a letter telling him if you guys do
start scalping enemy dead, you'll not only get court-martialed but you'll do
our whole campaign a disservice.";  The Army's code of ethics; Army lawyers
teach front-line troops rules of battlefield conduct.; Forbidden targets,
tactics, techniques;    1. Don't attack noncombatants;    2. Don't shoot at a
parachute unless it holds a combatant (an enemy pilot who has ejected is not a
combatant unless he resists surrender after landing; enemy paratroops are);   
3. Don't shoot at Red Cross or hide behind medical service symbols;    4.
Don't cause destruction beyond requirements of mission;    5. Don't attack
protected property (religious, art, science, archeology) unless enemy using
for military purposes;    6. Don't use poison or alter weapons to increase
enemy suffering; ...; Enemy captives and detainees;    1. Let enemy soldiers
