<HEAD>Bomb in University Injures 40 Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A firebomb ripped through a crowded
university lecture hall Friday and injured 40 students, including
13 who suffered severe burns, officials said.
   It was the third such bomb attack in just over a year at
universities in Brussels. No one has claimed responsibility for any
of the attacks.
   The bomb went off at 9 a.m. in a Louvain University auditorium
packed with about 100 students attending a pharmacy class, said a
police official who asked not to be named.
   The explosive device was hidden in a briefcase. It included
fluid soap, which has an effect like napalm when it is part of a
bomb, the official said.
   A similar bomb was used in a Dec 1, 1989 bomb attack at Brussels
University across town.
   ``There was a sudden blast, a big fire and part of the roof came
crashing down,'' said Paul Tulkens, who was in the class Friday.
Some students ran out with hair and clothes on fire. Evidence of a
firebomb was found in the hall, officials said.
   University spokesman Paul Macq said the university had not
received any threats or warnings.
</TEXT>
