<HL> Who's News:
Dow Chemical's Popoff Named President,
Will Succeed Oreffice as Chief in Late '87
---
By John Bussey
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 05/15/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> DOW WNEWS
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
DIVIDENDS (DIV) </IN>
<DATELINE> MIDLAND, Mich.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Chemical Co. named Frank P. Popoff president and chief operating officer and said he will succeed Paul F. Oreffice as chief executive officer later this year. 

   Mr. Popoff, 51 years old, had been the executive vice president responsible for all foreign operations, world-wide manufacturing and employee relations. 
He succeeds Mr. Oreffice as president, and is scheduled to become chief executive Dec. 1. 
The chief operating officer's post is a new one. 
Mr. Oreffice, 59, will remain chairman after Dec. 1. 

   In addition, the chemical company increased its quarterly dividend five cents to 55 cents a share, reflecting the board's "confidence in the sustained earnings" of Dow in the future, Mr. Oreffice said. 
The dividend is payable July 30 to stock of record June 30. 

   Mr. Oreffice also said he expects Dow to post record profit and sales for the second quarter. 
The previous record quarterly results came in the first period, when it reported profit of $246 million, or $1.28 a share, on sales of $3.02 billion. 

   Mr. Oreffice made his comments at the annual meeting. 
He said it is possible that Dow could reach $1 billion in profit this year if business remains strong, though he later emphasized that he wasn't making a forecast. 
In 1986, Dow Chemical earned $732 million, or $3.82 a share, on sales of $11.11 billion. 

   Mr. Popoff will take the reins of the big chemical and pharmaceuticals maker at one of the stronger moments in Dow's recent history. 
Under Mr. Oreffice, Dow has trimmed excess capacity in its basic chemicals operations, which contributed to $592 million in charges in 1985, and expanded its specialty chemicals businesses. 
Several years ago, the company set a goal of making specialty chemicals account for 50% of profit by 1987, a target Dow met last year. 
By comparison, when Dow began its push into specialty chemicals in 1978, the business contributed only about 15% of profit. 

   Lately, Dow has also reaped the benefits of some coincidental factors, such as lower raw materials expenses, especially oil, and a weakened dollar abroad, which has boosted exports. 

   There had been some speculation that Keith R. McKennon, group vice president and director of research and development, might be chosen as the new chief executive, but Mr. Popoff's broad marketing and international experience helped him win the new post. 
"Both Frank and I had a lot of international experience and I think, for a company that has over 50% of its sales outside (the U.S.), that's very important," Mr. Oreffice said. 

   Dow is increasing its business abroad; one sign of the company's increasingly international outlook is the fact that four of its 17 board members are foreign-born, including Mr. Oreffice, born in Italy, and Mr. Popoff, born in Bulgaria. 

   Mr. Popoff's previous positions with Dow include stints as general manager of the agricultural and organic chemicals department of Dow Chemical U.S.A. and vice president, marketing and sales, for Dow Chemical Europe. 
He has degrees in chemistry and business administration. 

   Mr. Popoff, who says he enjoys a good game of gin rummy, said "the road map has been drawn out" for Dow's corporate strategy, but he plans to do some "fine-tuning." 
Among other things, Dow will continue to expand its pharmaceuticals business and to try to carve out a bigger share of markets in countries such as Japan. 
As for research and development, Mr. Popoff believes that "the next round of success will go to those companies that get it right technologically." 

   Mr. Oreffice could remain chairman until he reaches age 65. 
He said that, once he steps down as chief executive, he plans to focus on his role as a representative of Dow. 
The chief executive, who often brags about his tennis game, also said he hopes to spend more time at his home in Scottsdale, Ariz., perfecting his game. 

   Dow Chemical has an unusually specific policy of "deceleration," which requires line managers to relinquish their line duties at age 60, or five years after their last significant promotion, whichever is later. 
Mr. Oreffice has been chief executive since 1978. 

   Hunter W. Henry, executive vice president, succeeds Mr. Popoff as head of all non-U.S. operations. 
Mr. Henry had been president of Dow Chemical U.S.A. Mr. McKennon was named to succeed Mr. Henry as head of U.S. operations. 

</TEXT>
