<CAPTION>  Drawing; DRAWING: Catherine Kanner--Los Angeles Times.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  LETTER  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  I commend your strong stance on American Indian self-rule (Editorials, Jan.
23), and agree that Native Americans can run their own lives at least as well
as the Bureau of Indian Affairs.;    I lived and worked on the Northern
Cheyenne Reservation for four years during the early '70s, developing a
writing system and native school curricula, and I saw firsthand the Indians'
frustration with the bureau's handling of their affairs, especially concerning
nearby coal reserves.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  IT'S HIGH TIME NATIVE AMERICANS RECEIVED
SELF RULE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Letters to the Editor  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Native Americans are no longer the uneducated savages as our historic guilt
has portrayed them. Perhaps the following joke, a favorite among the Cheyenne,
will show you how they view the Bureau of Indian Affairs:;    Just before
Custer headed out West to meet his destiny at Little Big Horn, he made the
rounds of various offices in Washington, D.C., to say his goodbyes. As he was
leaving the Bureau of Indian Affairs, he told them, "I'm going out West to
take care of this Indian problem. Don't do anything until I get back.";    --
Dan Hawkmoon Alford; Hayward; OBLIGATIONS COME WITH FINANCIAL AID; In response
to Aimee Allison's "Duty is to life, not to killing" (Commentary, Jan. 23): It
appears to me that Allison had a clear idea of her values concerning life and
a peaceful resolve of differences; she chose to eschew those values in return
for financial aid for college. She clearly states that she would be unable to
perform the job she was trained to do but makes no mention of how she was able
to justify accepting financial aid from the Army.;    Now that it is time to
honor a commitment to perform a job for which she was trained and compensated,
she has chosen not to fulfill her obligation. Perhaps this has a lesson for
Allison and others: Do not sell out your values for financial aid.;    -- Ken
Greenly; Cupertino; DON'T LET GULF WAR BLOT OUT OTHER ISSUES; Thank you for
not permitting the war in the Persian Gulf to let us forget other important
issues around the world. In particular, thanks for "Enough guns to Salvador"
(Editorials, Jan. 18).;    Our nation must be the undisputed world leader in
the protection of human rights. By giving money to the murdering government of
El Salvador we are perpetuating abuse and sending the message to the world
that this conduct not only bears our imprimatur but may be rewarded
financially.;    -- Woody Nedom; Los Gatos; Protest won't end; war in Middle
East; It will do no good whatsoever to protest U.S. involvement in the war in
the Persian Gulf. It takes two to tangle. Rather, we must find a way to get
both sides to end the war.;    As long as the warring continues, however, it
is unfair for the United States to assume most of the burden. The U.N.
resolution was multilateral. Therefore, let all who joined in the resolution
contribute resources to the effort until both sides agree to end it.;    What
would happen if the United States were to withdraw its forces? Would others
step in to fill the gap? Would Saddam Hussein proclaim victory and end the
war? Or would he step up his efforts, prompting intercession by other
countries?;    -- Lawrence Gold; Mountain View; Ecological warfare; leaves
lasting scars; In his war against the allies, Saddam Hussein has unleashed a
very frightening weapon: ecological sabotage. Setting fire to oil facilities
and dumping oil into bodies of water upon which so many depend must not become
an acceptable tool of warfare for anyone.;    War is terrible enough; it
should not be made worse by causing destruction which will far outlast the
conflict.;    -- Dan Haifley; Watsonville; Mention of 'draft'; triggers deja
vu;  I heard the dread words "military draft" and it sent shivers up my spine.
Deja vu -- it's been over 20 years, but suddenly it was like yesterday. But
this time the fear is for someone new: Instead of my brother and boyfriend, it
is for my son.;    I remember the words I read at Dachau. "History forgotten
is often repeated." Have we forgotten?;    Oh, the terms are new -- Scud
missiles instead of napalm, sorties instead of bombs, chemical warheads
instead of Agent Orange. But is the meaning any different? Are we any more
defending our country now than we were 20 years ago? North Vietnam was not
invading our shores any more than Iraq is now.;    Oh, I know about the oil.
But what if we spent the money we're now spending daily on the war on
alternative energy sources? Maybe we could lower our oil dependency.;    I
also know about Saddam Hussein and what a "Hitler" he is. But if you don't
think that he won't be replaced by another dictator, then you don't know the
history of the Middle East.;    Will our "war for peace" really bring peace?
Did 58,000 American deaths change anything 20 years ago? Vietnam is still
communist. Will American deaths change anything this time? Did we really
exhaust all diplomatic means of a settlement, or did we become impatient as
Americans often do? Would the sanctions have worked? These questions keep me
awake at night.;    Yes, I support the our troops in the Middle East coming
home alive; no, I don't support the reasons they're there. Yes, I would give
my life for my country, but no, I won't give my son's life for someone else's
country.;    -- Lynn Calhoun; Saratoga; Heterosexuals fail; to understand
gays; The homosexual predicament is not easily understood by heterosexuals,
and Joanne Jacobs (Commentary, Jan. 10) has not made noteworthy progress in
the direction.;    The compartmentalization of sexuality is simply not part of
the heterosexual experience, while it remains central to the gay experience.
To make a living and to survive on the streets has required that we be
straight-acting, letting down our guard only for moments in segregated
locales. This way of living saps our power and degenerates our sexuality. Now
it is being replaced with lives of integrity -- where honesty and candor
govern our social relations.;    Jacobs dismisses the movement by invoking a
call for privacy and manners. To suggest, as she does, that humans are sexual
only in the bedroom is akin to saying that humans are hungry only in the
dining room. Get real.;    -- Derek Schwartz; San Jose  </TEXT>
