<DESCRIPT>  OPINION; MIDEAST; WAR; END  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  'IT IS OUR belief that the best policy is not to involve ourselves in those
internal conflicts," said press secretary Marlin Fitzwater.;    The U.S. might
blockade a country's exports and imports, and then bomb it back to a
"pre-industrial age," destroying factories, power grids, water supplies,
communications lines, bridges and roads. President Bush might urge citizens of
another country to overthrow their Hitler-like leader. Along with the Security
Council, we might demand to monitor the destruction of a country's chemical
and biological weapons, nuclear weapons-grade material and ballistic missiles.
But intervene? Heavens, no.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SPOILING OUR PARADE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Joanne Jacobs, who writes a column on Mondays and Thursdays, is a member of
the Mercury News editorial pages staff.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     There are many ways to resolve internal conflicts. Some countries hold an
election to see which leadership the people favor. Albania just did that.
Others might use heavy artillery, tanks and helicopter gunships to shell
populated cities, slaughter rebels and their families and neighbors and
doctors and clergymen, and starve the survivors into submission, with a little
torture for educational and inspirational purposes. That's the Iraqi way.
Different strokes for different folks.;    President Bush "feels for those
people," says deputy White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk, but: "The issue of
internal unrest in Iraq is an issue that has to be settled between the
government and the people of Iraq. It's a decision for the people of Iraq to
make.";    And it is being settled, quite finally for tens of thousands of
Iraqis in Karbala and Kirkuk. The decision for the people of Iraq to make is:
Surrender or die? Flee into the mountains to starve and freeze, or stay in
town and get dragged behind a tank?;    It's their decision, and we must
respect that. Wouldn't want to impose our values.;    And besides, it's so
messy, isn't it? I mean, the Shiites are religious fundamentalists and the
Kurds are inconvenient nationalists and nobody's moderate or democratic or
pro-Western. They don't wear business suits and ties!;    Better to block
Iraqi oil exports, thereby preventing the rebuilding of the economy, and
continuing the suffering of the people, so they'll pressure Saddam into taking
early retirement. Oh, that's been tried. Well, maybe Saddam will step down to
save Iraq from suffering on his account. Hmm. Maybe not.;    Actually,
according to all the insider reports from Washington, President Bush never
wanted a revolt of the unwashed masses when he called for the overthrow of
Saddam. He wanted the military or political elite to take over, the sort of
people we know how to deal with. His theory is that once the Iraqi army puts
down the internal disputes, recovering its self-esteem, some nice, well-bred
general will stage a neat, little coup and kick out The Mustache, and Iraq
will stabilize under the New Improved (Blood) Baath Party, restoring the
balance of power and politik.;    It means: Stand by and let the Republican
Guard murder thousands of people till they suppress the popular will, and then
maybe they'll put in a different dictator with blood on a different pair of
hands.;    Normally, my enthusiasm for U.S. involvement in civil wars is
limited. I don't want to see us charging around the world righting wrongs,
especially if the good guys aren't all that good, which is usually the case.; 
  But we've already charged into Iraq. We occupy one-sixth of the country.
We're involved.;    And, pardon me, isn't it just a little late to worry about
stability? If we wanted stability, we should have let Saddam keep Kuwait. That
was a stable situation. For that matter, we should rebuild the Berlin Wall.;  
 As for the much-feared "Lebanonization" of Iraq, which means it might fall
into its original Shiite, Sunni and Kurdish parts, if the people of Iraq don't
want to be the people of Iraq, and it takes brutal repression to keep the
country together (the Kurds say they just want more autonomy), do we prefer
brutal repression to self-determination?;    Bush should have told Saddam
Hussein to ground the helicopter gunships, or see them turned into scrap
metal. Roll the tanks and artillery back to Baghdad. Send the Republican Guard
home for Ramadan. Cut it out.;    In fact, as long as we're ramming a cease
fire down Iraq's throat, why not insist that Iraq hold a free election -- like
the one Saddam Hussein proposed holding in Kuwait -- run by the United
Nations? If Albania is ready for democracy, why not Iraq?;    The threat alone
might do it. If they still remember the Crusaders, they should remember the
U.S. Air Force. And the Iraqi army isn't keen on fighting people who can fight
back.;    If we deny Saddam Hussein the use of his military machine, the
people of Iraq could settle their internal conflicts. Maybe they'd use rifles
but that's less bloody than helicopters and napalm. It would, as William
Safire says, level the killing field.;    Ironically, Iraqis won't curse
America for bombing Iraq. Saddam's troops have killed more civilians and done
more destruction, including devastating Shiite holy cities. Iraqis will curse
America for not bombing the Iraqi army when it turned on its own citizens.;   
President Bush will go down in history not as the liberator of Kuwait, but as
a silent accomplice to the murder of Iraqis who believed the United States
stood for freedom, justice and democracy, and found that all we cared about
was the balance of power, national borders and oil.;    Too bad, Shiites.
Tough luck, Kurds. Go away and die quietly. Don't bleed on our victory parade.  </TEXT>
